        "newspaperPageNumber":"4",
        "trailText":"<p>In Panorama interview, teenager who was shot by Taliban appeals to fellow pupils to regard her as 'a normal girl'</p>",
        "headline":"Malala Yousafzai urges British girls not to take education for granted",
        "body":"<p><a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/world/malala-yousafzai\" title=\"\">Malala Yousafzai</a>, the 16-year-old shot by the Taliban for promoting female education and who later became an international advocate for children's rights, has warned British girls not to take their schooling for granted.</p><p>The teenager appealed on a  <a href=\"http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b006t14n\" title=\"\">BBC Panorama programme</a>, to be broadcast on Monday, for pupils to regard her as \"as their friend and as a normal girl\".</p><p>Malala, now a pupil at Edgbaston School for Girls, urged British students to regard education as precious. \"Reading a book, having a pen in our hands, studying, sitting in a classroom is very special for us because once we were deprived [of] it and because [of] what we have seen in Swat.</p><p>\"Here they consider me a good girl, the girl who stood up for children's rights and the girl who was shot by the Taliban. They never look at me as Malala, as their friend, and as a normal girl. In Pakistan, I was just Malala, simply Malala.\"</p><p>She said she was missing her school and friends in the Swat valley but she insisted she was keeping true to her Pashtun culture amid plaudits for her stand after the gun attack on her last October.</p><p>Malala has been nominated for the <a href=\"http://www.nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/peace/\" title=\"\">Nobel peace prize</a> (the winner is announced Friday) and has been honoured at the <a href=\"http://www.un.org/en/\" title=\"\">UN</a>,<a href=\"http://www.harvard.edu\" title=\"\"> at Harvard University</a>, and in her \"second home\", Birmingham. She has also been invited to a reception hosted by the Queen at Buckingham Palace on 18 October.</p><p>Malala, whose father, Ziauddin, was an anti-Taliban activist, told how she had been targeted after challenging a Taliban edict that girls should not go to school; she broadcast her views on a BBC online diary and appeared on Pakistani TV. Taliban punishments in her home town of Mingora included \"throwing acid on women's faces or abusing them or killing them\", she said.</p><p>She added: \"I was afraid for my future. And at that time there  was fear all around us, in every street and in every square of Mingora. At that time I said if we want to fight against the fear let us have the power to speak up.</p><p>\"When I heard about the threats from the Taliban, I used to think that a Talib would come and he would shoot you, Malala, on the street.\"</p><p>Malala was shot in the head on a bus going home from school. \"We were having exams that week and the paper on 9 October went very well. It was Pakistan studies, but the paper one day before was physics. I love physics, but it was hard.\"</p><p>She had been told by her mother to take the bus rather than walk as it was safer. \"I was just talking to Moniba [a friend] and having a gossip … everything seemed as normal part of life.\" She did not remember what happened next.</p><p>Friends said two boys boarded the bus as it slowed for a corner.</p><p>Shazia, one of the friends, said: \"One of them came round the back and said 'who is Malala Yousafzai?'\"</p><p>Moniba, another friend, said: \"She was very scared at the time and didn't say anything.\" Kainat, a friend, added: \"Then he fired straight at her. I saw a lot of blood on Malala's head. When I saw that blood, I fell unconscious.\"</p><p>\"My clothes, my shoes, my socks, my pouch, my books, all that was just full of blood,\" said Moniba. \"Malala's blood.\"</p><p>Malala, who was near death, was taken to hospital. \"I have pictures still in my mind. In one picture, suddenly I see my father on my left side and when I look at him, I just tell him something and then I just close my eyes and everything goes dark. I thought I'm dead.\"</p><p>She was airlifted to a military hospital in Peshawar where she had life-saving surgery, then British doctors visiting Pakistan advised taking her Birmingham for further care. Her family followed and over the next four months Malala had several operations.</p><p>Her contact with the west has been criticised in Pakistan. But she said: \"No, I'm not becoming western, I am still following my Pashtun culture and I'm wearing a shalvar kamiz, a dupatta on my head. And I believe Islam is a true religion and it teaches us how to be patient and how to tolerate other religions and it teaches us about peace. Islam means peace.</p><p>\"I don't know why people have divided the whole world into two groups, west and east. Education is neither eastern nor western. Education is education and it's the right of every human being.\"</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/419192247|2013-10-14T15:55:37Z|2063861e6d5b3930881ab880e40513afab496576 -->",
